== Assembly Code ==

=== Main Entry ($9fb9) ===

<pre>
$9fb9: jsr $a038    ; Initialize - parse character data
$9fbc: lda #$00
$9fbe: sta $6e3b    ; Threshold index = 0
$9fc1: sta $0e      ; Level counter
$9fc3: inc $0e      ; Level = 1
$9fc5: inc $0e      ; Level = 2
...
$9fcf: lda $7b      ; Load initial value
$9fd1: sta $00      ; Delta = initial
$9fd3: sta $04      ; Total = initial
</pre>

=== Main Loop ($9fe9-$a037) ===

<pre>
$9ffa: ldy $6e3b        ; Y = threshold index
$9ffd: lda ($0c),y      ; Load threshold byte
$9fff: ldx $6e3b
$a002: bne $a006        ; If not first byte...
$a004: and #$1f         ; ...mask to 5 bits
$a006: and #$7f         ; Mask to 7 bits
$a008: cmp $0e          ; Compare with level
$a00a: bcs $a01c        ; If threshold >= level, skip
$a013: inc $6e3a        ; Advance rate index
$a016: inc $6e3b        ; Advance threshold index
$a019: jmp $9ffa        ; Loop to check next threshold

$a01c: ldx $6e3a        ; X = rate index
$a01f: lda $a259,x      ; Load rate from table
$a022: ldx #$04         ; X = 4 (work area offset)
$a024: jsr $a07d        ; Call multiply subroutine
$a027: ldy #$00
$a029: jsr $a0df        ; Add delta to total
$a02c: lda $0e
$a02e: cmp $0a          ; Check if level == target
$a030: beq $a037        ; If yes, done
$a032: inc $0e          ; Level++
$a034: jmp $9fe9        ; Continue loop
$a037: rts
</pre>

=== Multiply Subroutine ($a07d) ===

Performs: <code>result = (value × rate) >> 4</code>

Uses shift-and-add multiplication followed by 4-bit right shift. The subroutine handles 16-bit multiplication with an 8-bit rate.

== Notes ==

* Some online sources (e.g., woodus.com) have incorrect values for levels 6-9
* All values verified against emulator memory dumps at actual level-ups
* The formula produces exact matches for L2-L5 and L10 across all tested characters
* Threshold 4 is typically 99, meaning the final rate applies from that threshold to max level

